    "created_at": "2025-01-12T23:24:26Z",
    "updated_at": "2025-01-12T23:24:26Z",
    "body": "`sudo su` is how I switch between user accounts.  Simply `sudo` does not start a new session and so the variables would remain.  Maybe someone smarter than me knows how to switch accounts and keep certain variables inherited from the parent process.  I tried `sudo su -m otheraccount` but it failed with permission errors. This is a nice to have and maybe not practically achievable with starship.\r\n\r\n```\r\n❯ sudo su -m otheracct\r\nbash: /root/.bashrc: Permission denied\r\nUnable to create log dir \"/root/.cache/starship\": Os { code: 13, kind: PermissionDenied, message: \"Permission denied\" }!\r\nUnable to open session log file \"/root/.cache/starship/session_.log\": Os { code: 13, kind: PermissionDenied, message: \"Permission denied\" }!\r\n```\r\n",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "pin": null,
