    "created_at": "2025-05-01T23:32:42Z",
    "updated_at": "2025-05-01T23:34:56Z",
    "body": "I have discovered a way to do this. Simply use:\n\n```bash\nsudo -E su -m otheracct\n\n# Or if you want to only use sudo\nsudo -E -u otheracct shell\n\n# As an example to change into the root user with zsh as a shell\nsudo -E -u root zsh\n\n# You can just do this if you are not using ssh, su -m also works.\nsudo -iu otheracct\n```\n\nAnother solution is adding your user to the wheel group so you can use the su -m command without sudo, but that may not be possible/allowed on the target machine.",
